column2: Communist Party of the Pequot People
Radicals want to strengthen the bourgeoisie at the expense of the aristocracy, but care little for the proletariat.

The Citizen Guard are militant liberals who have risen up in rebellion against the, real or perceived, oppressive practices of the government and the state apparatus, seeking to protect their rights as citizens, whatever the cost. Fighting against the corrupt state, these revolutionaries consider themselves to be true patriots.

A group of liberals disgruntled with their lack of political freedom, and the pace of parliamentary reform, have formed a new faction in $COUNTRY_ADJ$ politics. The Radicals are the revolutionary champions of Reason, and they will not hesitate to use whatever means necessary to see their ideas of liberty and equality instituted both in $COUNTRY$ and abroad.
Anarchists want reforms, but do not engage in parliamentary politics. They only engage with the law when the State withers away into the Commune.
Workers are encouraged to form new industrial cooperatives, but members of the bourgeoise have withdrawn from economic activity.
Democracy is exercised by the working classes, but the upper echelons of the bourgeoisie are effectively excluded from participation in government.
Seats are allocated proportionally within a party list voting system.

Comprised of aggrieved workers and left-wing militants, these rebels vow to fight to overthrow the nation's institutions as they stand and implement what they view to be a more just and equitable system of government.

Our restive subjects in Hispania do not view themselves as Mauretanians, and begrudge what they deem to be 'foreign' rule. An easy way to mitigate this would be to acknowledge Spania as a separate realm- one nonetheless ruled by the Mauretanian court. If we claimed the crown of Hispania, and let the Spanians hold their own assemblies while still acknowledging our overall rule, we might be able to nip Spanish unrest in the bud.

The only territories effectively controlled by us are those that hug the Mediterranean coast, but our ancient claims extend far into the African interior. The Great Powers are finally realizing the value of Africa- if we do not move to stake our claims now, we may lose them forever.
Mutapa sits in a key and vulnerable corner of Africa. If we do not move to secure its loyalties now, another Power may do so.
Ceylon is a valuable island, one underutilized by its Gujarati lords. Our expertise and technology could open up a world of wonders there- if we had control of the place.

The Maldives are a strategically valuable archipelago, not fully appreciated by Gujarat. In our hands, it could become the lynchpin of the Indian Ocean- if we could convince Gujarat to part with the islands.

Romania foundation is based on Romanitas, its name proudly telling all that its land is the land of Romans. And yet, Romania doesn't even control the whole heartland of Ancient Rome, the Italian Peninsula. It is only right (and will help placate nationalists) to claim what the ancient Romans had as our own!
Declaration of the Rights of Man

The Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen, a fundamental document of the Britannian Revolution, defined the individual and collective rights of all the estates of the realm as universal.
For some cultures, the notion of democracy and individual freedom is rooted in their very psyche.
